1
00:00:00,001 --> 00:00:09,500
In this session, we will explore the importance of using a security plugin and better understand specific settings to help you fortify your site.

2
00:00:09,500 --> 00:00:22,400
The Plugin Directory contains many plugins worth exploring, such as WordFence, All-in-One Security and Firewall, Jetback, Sucuri, Solid Security, etc.

3
00:00:22,400 --> 00:00:32,300
It is important to note that some plugins offer more options or settings than others. Premium packages also unlock additional functionalities.

4
00:00:32,300 --> 00:00:40,400
Depending on the plugin you've chosen, here are a few features worth considering. Number one, audits and scans.

5
00:00:40,400 --> 00:00:48,200
It is advised to conduct regular security audits or scans to help identify potential vulnerabilities on your website.

6
00:00:48,200 --> 00:00:55,000
Using a security plugin makes this process straightforward and manageable, without technical expertise.

7
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:10,900
Most plugins allow you to enable auto scans and regularly scans your WordPress site for security threats and performs automated backups to safeguard your website's data, providing comprehensive protection with easy one-click restores.

8
00:01:10,900 --> 00:01:21,800
Manual audits are also important. There's always a chance a security tool misses a malicious file dropped by an attacker or doesn't notice a suspicious user.

9
00:01:21,800 --> 00:01:27,700
Secondly, some plugins allow you to enable a web application firewall.

10
00:01:27,700 --> 00:01:35,700
A web application firewall adds an extra layer of security by monitoring and filtering incoming traffic to your website.

11
00:01:35,700 --> 00:01:44,600
It is like having a security guard for your website. It stands between your site and the internet, checking all the data that comes in and goes out.

12
00:01:44,600 --> 00:01:49,600
If it sees anything suspicious, it blocks it to keep your site safe.

13
00:01:49,600 --> 00:01:53,800
The next option worth setting up is IP address detection.

14
00:01:53,800 --> 00:02:00,000
IP address detection helps the plugin identify the IP addresses or visitors to your website.

15
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:08,400
This is crucial for security features like blocking malicious users or limiting login attempts from specific IP addresses.

16
00:02:08,400 --> 00:02:16,300
If the plugin can't correctly detect IP addresses, it may not properly block harmful traffic or limit access we needed.

17
00:02:16,300 --> 00:02:26,600
By correctly detecting IP addresses, security tools can enforce access restrictions, block suspicious activity and safeguard the website's integrity.

18
00:02:26,600 --> 00:02:31,200
You can usually enter a list of IP addresses that should not be locked out.

19
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:36,200
WordFence for example provides several options for detecting IP addresses.

20
00:02:36,200 --> 00:02:39,800
The first option is the default recommended option.

21
00:02:39,800 --> 00:02:45,200
The second option is to use PHP's built-in remote ADDR.

22
00:02:45,200 --> 00:02:54,400
Remote ADDR is a server variable that tells you the IP address of the computer or device that is accessing your website.

23
00:02:54,400 --> 00:03:03,000
If we look at a different plugin, we'll see using remote ADDR is the default option for the All-in-One Security and Firewall plugin,

24
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:10,000
which is below Advanced settings and very secure, but it must be set up correctly to work.

25
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,800
IP address detection always requires proper server configuration

26
00:03:14,800 --> 00:03:20,100
otherwise IP addresses can easily be spoofed or disguised.

27
00:03:20,100 --> 00:03:31,300
If you are behind any sort of proxy, for example a load balancer, the reliability of this method may be compromised as the PHP code cannot ascertain the server's configuration.

28
00:03:31,300 --> 00:03:40,700
An important step when setting up IP address detection is therefore proper server configuration, which needs hosting provider intervention.

29
00:03:40,700 --> 00:03:49,500
Ensure you contact your hosting provider to understand how your server is configured so that you can select the correct IP detection method.

30
00:03:49,500 --> 00:03:54,900
Next, some plugins also allow you to secure your WordPress configuration file.

31
00:03:54,900 --> 00:04:06,300
The wp-config.php file contains sensitive information such as database credentials, security keys and other configuration parameters.

32
00:04:06,300 --> 00:04:12,300
Securing this file can prevent unauthorized access and potential exploitation.

33
00:04:12,300 --> 00:04:20,300
When using the All-in-One Security plugin for example, you can set the recommended permissions when selecting File Security.

34
00:04:20,300 --> 00:04:25,500
Additionally, enabling brute force protection on your WordPress site is crucial.

35
00:04:25,500 --> 00:04:36,900
Brute force attacks are common methods hackers use to gain unauthorized access to your website by repeatedly trying different username and password combinations until they find the correct one.

36
00:04:36,900 --> 00:04:51,300
Brute force protection stops unauthorized users from accessing your site by limiting login attempts, blocking suspicious IP addresses and verifying that real people are logging in through captcha challenges.

37
00:04:51,300 --> 00:04:57,100
The settings for brute force attack protection may of course vary between security plugins.

38
00:04:57,100 --> 00:05:04,300
Lastly, setting up two-factor authentication to protect your site from brute force attacks is also advised.

39
00:05:04,300 --> 00:05:12,700
In addition to robust password management, enabling two-factor authentication is crucial for enhancing the security of your WordPress site.

40
00:05:12,700 --> 00:05:27,300
Two-factor authentication adds a layer of protection to your login process by requiring your password and a second verification form, such as a unique code sent to your mobile device or generated by an authentication app.

41
00:05:27,300 --> 00:05:34,500
This additional step significantly reduces the risk of unauthorized access, even if your password is compromised.

42
00:05:34,500 --> 00:05:43,700
Many security plugins, including Wordfence and All-in-One WordPress Security and Firewall, offer built-in support for two-factor authentication.

43
00:05:43,700 --> 00:05:51,000
Finally, it is also worth mentioning that good security should always be backed by a good backup strategy.

44
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:57,300
In the event of an incident, this allows you to quickly recover and restore your data from backups.

45
00:05:57,300 --> 00:06:01,500
And get an SSL certificate if you don't have one.

46
00:06:01,500 --> 00:06:12,400
An SSL certificate, which stands for Secure Sockets Layer, secures your website by encrypting data between your site and visitors, protecting sensitive information from hackers.

47
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:25,300
It also makes your site more trustworthy and can improve search engine rankings. You can buy an SSL certificate from a provider or use a free service like Let's Encrypt.

48
00:06:25,300 --> 00:06:31,400
Many web hosts automatically provide and install SSL certificates as part of their packages.

49
00:06:31,400 --> 00:06:38,000
So check with your host to enable it with just a few clicks in your hosting dashboard, if not activated.

50
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Implementing all these security measures we discussed can significantly enhance the protection of your site against more sophisticated threats.

